* Contents:
============

* What does the program do?
===========================

The program main_5_a.c implements part (a) of Exercise 5.

It creates a named pipe (FIFO) and then spawns two child processes.
Each child process executes a different program:

- The first child runs consumer.c, which acts as the consumer.
- The second child runs producer.c, which acts as the producer.

The producer reads data from an input file in fixed-size chunks and
writes it to the named pipe at regular intervals.

The consumer reads data from the pipe and writes it to an output file.

The process continues until all input data has been consumed.

---

The program includes automatic cleanup of the named pipe after successful
execution or in case of an error.

It also handles the SIGINT signal (Ctrl+C). In this case, the pipe is
also properly removed to prevent leftover resources.

---

Both consumer.c and producer.c accept:
- input/output file arguments
- an additional mode argument used for Exercise 5b

---

* Exercise 5b behavior:
=======================

In part (b), both programs are executed independently using xterm,
instead of being created by a parent process.

The main difference compared to part (a) is:
- processes are not related (independent execution)
- the named pipe is created externally (from the shell)
- both programs receive the pipe name as a command-line argument

Aside from that, functionality remains the same.

---

* Mode argument:
================

- Mode = 1:
  Programs open the named pipe using its file name.

- Mode = 2:
  Programs use an alternative file descriptor approach where the pipe
  is opened using a command-line provided reference.

---

* How to run the program:
=========================

To compile:
make

To run part (a):
make run_a

To run part (b):
make run_b

To clean build files:
make clean

To remove the pipe:
make clean_pipe

To verify correctness:
make check
